result.execSummary:
The defendant Kirsten A Nadolski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Kirsten A Nadolski is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Kirsten A Nadolski was found guilty of 1st Reckless Homicide/Deliver Drugs, a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.02(2)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes:
Restitution due during term of extended supervison.
The restitution amount listed reflects an additional Administrative Cost of 10% of the amount of restitution pursuant to Section 973.06(1)(g).  The 5% Restitution Surcharge is equal to 5% of the total of the restitution, costs, attorney fees, and fines, pursuant to Section 973.20(11)(a).
Costs and restitution are due during term of supervision.

Defendant Kirsten A Nadolski in court with attorney Rachel Marie Alme-Boaz.  Defendant in custody. Adam Yale Gerol appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant enters no contest plea to Ct. 1. Court examines defendant, finds her guilty. Counsel recommend presentence investigation. At time of the sentencing, State will recommend 13 years prison-5 years initial confinement and 8 years extended supervision with conditions as well as restitution $8386.57. Court is informed the restitution amount has been submitted to the crime compensation fund but as of today there is not a response.  Court orders a presentence investigation be completed. On motion of the State, Court orders Ct. 2 dismissed. Defendant remanded pending sentencing.
